This won&#39;t solve your Keycloak admin client usage issue, but, if your API is configured as a resource server with JWT decoder, a much more efficient way to expose current user attributes is reflecting access token claims (this saves calls to Keycloak):
```java
@RestController
public class UserController {

	@GetMapping(&quot;/me&quot;)
	@PreAuthorize(&quot;isAuthenticated()&quot;)
	public Map&lt;String, Object&gt; getMe(JwtAuthenticationToken auth) {
		return auth.getTokenAttributes();
	}
}
```
You could use a path matcher in the security configuration instead of method security as done here, but don&#39;t forget to check for a valid authentication or you might have an `AnonymousAuthenticationToken` in the security context (instead of the `JwtAuthenticationToken` as expected by the code above).

If you prefer an empty map rather than a 401 for anonymous requests, you could do this instead:
```java
@RestController
public class UserController {

	@GetMapping(&quot;/me&quot;)
	public Map&lt;String, Object&gt; getMe(Authentication auth) {
		if (auth instanceof JwtAuthenticationToken jwt) {
			return jwt.getTokenAttributes();
		}
		return Map.of();
	}
}
```

