You shouldn&#39;t construct complicated xpath and get second text, using it.
Selenium can deal with `WebElements`, Corn is not `WebElement`, it&#39;s textContent of `address` element.

Instead of it, you just need to get text of `address` element, split it and assert second element from array (or store it).

```java
String text = driver.findElement(new By.ByTagName(&quot;address&quot;)).getText();
String[] address = text.split(System.lineSeparator());
Assert.assertEquals(address[1], &quot;Corn&quot;);
```

Note that `xmlns:name=&quot;...&quot;` only associates a namespace with a prefix. Any element with this prefix will belong to the associated namespace. Elements without prefix belong to the default namespace.

Thus ...
* In your first example namespace C is never used.
* In your second example the only namespace used is the default one, because neither element has a prefix.

Aside from that it doesn&#39;t matter where you put your namespace declarations, as long as they are being declared when you need them.

```
&lt;A xmlns=&quot;A&quot; xmlns:ns2=&quot;B&quot;&gt;
&lt;t1&gt;content&lt;/t1&gt;
&lt;t2&gt;
    &lt;ns2:t3&gt;
        &lt;ns2:t4&gt;content2&lt;/ns2:t4&gt;           
    &lt;/ns2:t3&gt;       
&lt;/t2&gt;
&lt;/A&gt;
```
is equivalent to
```
&lt;A xmlns=&quot;A&quot;&gt;
&lt;t1&gt;content&lt;/t1&gt;
&lt;t2&gt;
    &lt;ns2:t3 xmlns:ns2=&quot;B&quot;&gt;
        &lt;ns2:t4&gt;content2&lt;/ns2:t4&gt;           
    &lt;/ns2:t3&gt;       
&lt;/t2&gt;
&lt;/A&gt;
```

When using JAXB you will have to define the namespaces with the XmlElement-annotations:
```
@XmlElement(name = &quot;t3&quot;, namespace = &quot;B&quot;)
protected T3 t3;
```
Repeat this for any other element that should belong to this namespace.

