    public class CloudRecognition {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
            String A = scanner.nextLine();
            String B = scanner.nextLine();
            
            int n = A.length();
            Map&lt;Character, Integer&gt; indexMap = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
            
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++) {
                char ai = A.charAt(i);
                char bi = B.charAt(i);
                
                if (ai == bi) {
                    System.out.print(&quot;P&quot;);
                } else {
                    // Check if ai is present in indexMap
                    if (indexMap.containsKey(ai)) {
                        System.out.print(&quot;S&quot;);
                    } else {
                        indexMap.put(ai, i);
                        System.out.print(&quot;I&quot;);
                    }
                }
            }
            
            scanner.close();
        }
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Here&#39;s how the code works:

It reads the strings A and B from the input.

For each position i (1 ≤ i ≤ N), it compares the characters Ai and Bi.

If they are equal, it prints &quot;P&quot; (plagiarism).

If they are not equal, it checks whether the character Ai has appeared before. If it has, it prints &quot;S&quot; (suspicious). If it hasn&#39;t, it prints &quot;I&quot; (innocent) and adds Ai to the indexMap with the index i.

The indexMap is used to keep track of the positions where characters from string A have appeared before. This way, we prioritize the leftmost appearance for suspicious matches.
